Analysis of medical publications about COVID-19¶

With the current pandemic ongoing, the situation has led to trigger an unpredictable number of medical researches with the motive for finding treatments as well as vaccines as early as possible. The current circumstances have also directed to make efforts in gathering research publications along with the retrieval of text information in order to do text mining. Here in this assessment, we will be using a part of most commonly implemented resource of this type: CORD-19. To add to that, this specific resource can be available through various outlets, one of the most popular is Kaggle and the link is given below:

https://www.kaggle.com/allen-institute-for-ai/CORD-19-research-challenge

Initially, we will be making usage of Kaggle's subset data gathered in the file named as "metadata.csv" that is in csv format.

Task 2- What are the main clusters?¶

Here in this part, we will be fetching the text from the 'abstracts' in given data set for clustering and visualisation process. For clustering the data set, we will be making use of KMeans clustering algorithm. K-means clustering is defined as an approach for vector quantization process, initially from signal processing, that points to divide n observations to k clusters where each of the consideration applies to cluster with the adjacent mean, performing as a model of the collection.

Vectorization¶

Converting the data into a format that can be implemented by our algorithms. Tf-idf will be used in order to achieve this transforation that helps in conversion of our string formatted data to an aspect of how crucial each of the word is to the occurence out of journal.

For the vectorization of data, clustering approach has been selected depending on the context of 'abstract'.

In [18]:
def Stem_Tok(tokens):
    return [stem.stem(token) for token in tokens]
remove_punct = dict((ord(punct), None) for punct in string.punctuation)

def Stem_Norm(text):
    return Stem_Tok(nltk.word_tokenize(text.lower().translate(remove_punct)))

def Lem_Tok(tokens):
    return [lem.lemmatize(token) for token in tokens]
remove_punct = dict((ord(punct), None) for punct in string.punctuation)

def Lem_Norm(text):
    return Lem_Tok(nltk.word_tokenize(text.lower().translate(remove_punct)))

count_vect = CountVectorizer(max_df = 0.8, max_features = 10000, tokenizer=Lem_Norm, stop_words='english')
vect_tfidf = count_vect.fit_transform(meta_df["Abstract"].apply(lambda x: np.str_(x)))

pca_val = PCA(n_components = 0.97, random_state=90)
pca_val.fit(meta_df[["Journal", "Authors", "First Source", "License", "VectsData"]])
scores_pca_val = pca_val.transform(meta_df[["Journal", "Authors", "First Source", "License", "VectsData"]])

distortions_val = []
K = range(2, 30)
for j in K:
  kmeans_pca_val = KMeans(n_clusters=j, algorithm= 'auto', init="k-means++", n_init=j, random_state=0)
  kmeans_pca_val.fit(scores_pca_val)
  distortions_val.append(sum(np.min(cdist(scores_pca_val, kmeans_pca_val.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / meta_df.shape[0])

In [25]:
from wordcloud import WordCloud
def cleaned(txt):
  w = []
  regex_s = re.sub(r"[,.;@#?!&$]+", ' ', txt)
  regex_s = re.sub(r"\s+", ' ', regex_s)
  for word in regex_s.split():
    if word not in stopwords:
      w.append(lemma.lemmatize(word))
  return w

clust_n = 0
word_df = meta_df[meta_df["y"] == clust_n]
lemma = WordNetLemmatizer()
rep_words = [cleaned(x) for x in word_df["Abstract"]]
auth_words = []
for rep_list in rep_words:
  for rep_word in rep_list:
    auth_words.append(rep_word)

In [31]:
def comp_coherent_val(corp, dict, k):
    print(k)
    lda_mod = gensim.models.LdaMulticore(corpus=corp,
                                           id2word=dict,
                                           num_topics=k, 
                                           random_state=99,
                                           chunksize=99,
                                           passes=10)
    
    coherent_mod_lda = gensim.models.CoherenceModel(model=lda_mod, texts=rep_words, dictionary=dict, coherence='c_v')
    return coherent_mod_lda.get_coherence()


top_range = range(3, 10, 1)
score_l = {}
for k in top_range:
  cv = comp_coherent_val(corp=dt_matrix, dict=dict, k=k)
  score_l[k] = cv
print(score_l)

def f_top(row):
    if (row.loc[row>0.9]).any():
        return row.loc[row>0.9].index[0]
    else:
        return None
    
def f_prop(row):
    if (row.loc[row>0.9]).any():
        return row.loc[row>0.9].values[0]
    else:
        return None
    
new_data['Topic'] = new_data.loc[:, new_data.columns !='Abstract'].apply(f_top, axis = 1)
new_data['Propensity'] = new_data.iloc[:, 0:9].apply(f_prop, axis = 1)
new_data.drop(columns=new_data.columns[:10], inplace=True)

The figure represents frquency of each of the topics throughout all of the clusters. Taking the reference from above implementations and visualizations, following questions can be answered:

  1. Are there any topics that are more (or less) common in the clusters?
  • As per the chart illustrated above, it can be stated that some of the topics are occuring frequently through several clusters.
  1. For each topic, what are the most representative clusters?
  • Taking the reference from chart, we can conclude that cluster 9 is most representative cluster for topic 5 whereas cluster 2 is most representative cluster for topic 6 and likewise.
  1. For each cluster, what are its most representative topics?
  • The bar diagram above depicts that the data for each of the clusters is shown along with the frequency of topics framed in y-axis.

  • Finally, some furthermore informations such as distribution of authors and several more metrics can also be fetched from the topic modelling. To conclude, with the usage of topic modelling prior to the clustering, we can fetch better defined clusters.
